, and Asian crises—have played a central role in world affairs and continue to occur at an alarming rate, many questions about their causes and effects remain to be answered. In this wide-ranging volume, some of the best minds in economics focus on the historical and theoretical aspects of currency crises to investigate three fundamental issues: What drives currency crises? How should government behavior be modeled? And what are the actual consequences to the real economy? Reflecting the latest thinking on the subject, this offering from the NBER will serve as a useful basis for further debate on the theory and practice of speculative attacks, as well as a valuable resource as new crises loom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCurrency question -- History -- 20th century. 0aCurrency questionxHistoryy20th century. 0aFinancial crises -- History -- 20th century. 0aFinancial crisesxHistoryy20th century. 0aForeign exchange -- History -- 20th century. 0aForeign exchangexHistoryy20th century. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  acurrency, monetary policy, exchange rates, devaluation, investment, foreign markets, economics, nonfiction, latin america, europe, mexico, asia, speculative attacks, unemployment, private sector, macroeconomics, erm, peso, euro, balance of payments, emerging market, sovereign governments, capital, finance, economy, trade, profit, business.1 aCalvo, Guillermo A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrazen, Allan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Sebastian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEichengreen, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlood, Robert P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrankel